chargeHist.descr: Delivery of Schedule I or II Narcotics

result.execSummary:
The defendant Alexander J Enk was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manufacture/Deliver THC (<=200g), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(h)1.
  • Delivery of Schedule I or II Narcotics, a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

2:59 p.m.  Defendant in custoday and present in court with Atty Kristina Sanders-Brown.  Andrew Christenson for the State of Wisconsin.  Statement by Atty Sanders-Brown - matter has settled, defendant will plea to counts 1 & 3 and the balance of the counts will be dismissed and read-in and free to argue.  State concurs.  Atty Sanders-Brown concurs.  Defendant concurs.

Court goes over plea questionnaire with the defendant.  Court goes over constitutional rights with the defendant - defendant waives these rights.  Court goes over the elements of each offense.  Court instructs defendant of the maximum penalty.  Court instructs defendant regarding deportation.  (If felony) Court instructs regarding felony prohibitions.

Defendant enters a plea of NO CONTEST.  Court finds the plea is made freely, voluntarily, intelligently and understandingly.  Court finds there is a factual basis to support the plea.  Court finds the defendant guilty on counts 1 and strikes the place enhancer and finds the defendant guilty on count 3.  Court orders the balance of the counts (2,4,5 & 6) be dismissed and read-in.  Court orders the judgment of conviction be entered here today.  Statement by Bob Dore.  Statement by Kacey Powless.  Sentencing statement by DA.  Sentencing argument by Atty Sanders-Brown.  Statement by the defendant.

Court sentences the defendant to:  (COUNTS 1 & 3)

1 year of Initial Confinement and 2 years of Extended Supervision - consecutive to each other and consecutive to any other sentence.  Sentence to commence immediately.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION (EACH COUNT 1 & 3)

-Court costs.
-Defendant is to submit a DNA Sample.
-Defendant is to abide by all rules and recommendations of the supervising agent including any counseling and/or treatment as recommended.
-AODA and any follow-up
-Defendant is to maintain absolute sobriety - not to possess or consume any alcohol, illegal drugs or prescription drugs without a valid prescription.
-Defendant is not to be around those using illegal drugs or where drugs are present.
-Defendant is to seek or maintain employment.

Court finds the defendant eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.

Court will not grant sentence credit at this time.  Atty Sanders-Brown to submit something in writing.

Court adjourned at 3:22 p.m.
